                    <h2 class="card-header">Basic Investing Principles</h2>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h5 class="card-title">These are some pretty basic core investing principles:</h5>
                        <p class="card-text">
                            <div class="row">
                                <div class="col-md-7 p-0 mr-0">
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>Only invest with money you won't need within the next 3-5 Years
                                            <details> <summary class = "bottom-border">More Info</summary>
                                                If the stock market crashes, or the economy goes into depression, or you lose your job,
                                                you don't want to be forced to sell at the lows when you really should be buying instead.
                                            </details>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>The Major Stock Market Indexes (Like the S&P500 & Dow Jones etc) will always go up in the long run. 
                                            <details> <summary class = "bottom-border">More Info</summary>
                                                This is due to inflation, population growth,
                                                productivity growth and index rebalancing.
                                            </details>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Never act on predictions of analysts or economists in the news, they are all idiots. Don't invest based on where you predict the market will go in the
                                            short term. 
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            The Stock market and the economy don't move together. The stock market tends to be ahead by 6-12 months and will bottom just as recessions start.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Trying to time the market by selling at tops and buying at bottoms won't pan out well for you.
                                            <details> <summary class = "bottom-border">More Info</summary>
                                                It's Cliche, but time in the markets beats timing the markets, the majority of stock gains are made in single days. Here is a graph of your returns
                                                if you missed just a few of the best performing days in the market:
                                                <img src="/images/difficulty_to_time_market.jpg" alt="">
                                            </details>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Invest in fundamentally great businesses with conservative debt, strong economic moats and a strong track record of increasing earnings and cash flow.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Paying too much for a great business is a bad investment.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Maintain a diversified portfolio of defensive, growth, ETFs, speculative, and cyclical stocks across various industries.
                                            <details> <summary class = "bottom-border">More Info</summary>
                                                An example allocation would be 40% growth, 35% defensive, 10% ETFs, 5% cylical, 5% speculative, and 5% turnarounds. However, this is largely down to one's needs
                                                and how much drawdown they are willing to risk. For example, Youths in their 20's can have 50% growth, 30% defensive, 10% speculative, and 10% ETFs.
                                            </details>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                </div>
                                <div class="col-md-3 offset-md-1">
                                    <div class="blockquote-container">
                                        <blockquote class="blockquote p-0 mb-0 ml-0">
                                            <p>
                                                “The stock market is a device for transferring money from the impatient to the patient”
                                            <footer class="blockquote-footer">Warren Buffet</footer></p>
                                        </blockquote>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </p>
